GM calls new pickup truck in the United States to repair the seat backrest back
General Motors calls nearly 19000 of its brand-new Chevrolet Silverado and GMC Sierra pickup truck with built in 2014, in order to fix a problem with the manually adjustable seat backrest, a statement from the US regulatory authority on vehicle safety on Friday.
For some of the car, there can be a defect in the mechanism for the shelving of the Vordersitzlehne.
For this reason, they do not meet the federal guidelines for vehicle safety for head restraints.
"If had ascended from the back of the vehicle, it is possible that the head restraint not properly protects the occupants, so there is an increased risk of Verletzungs," read the message on the website of the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA).
The revoked models were produced between 1 August and 10 September.
The delivery of the GM trucks began in June and is the most important model launch of the leading American car manufacturer since the bankruptcy restructuring in 2009.
GM informed the vehicle owners in the first half of October about the defect.
